  <h3>Short biography by <u><a href="/the-researcher" target="_blank">Louise Watson</a></u></h3>
  <p>Jessica grew up with her non-indigenous mother in Notre Dame, a village near <a href source="/the-communities/Manawan">Odanak</a>. Unlike other Abenaki families, her father, her two brothers and sister live on the other side of the border, in various regions of the United States. Her educational journey has been a bit chaotic, and she had many jobs since her training as a hairdresser in 2011, and her start at Kiuna in 2014/2015. Two years ago, she started being involved in Quebec Native Women Inc., in the Youth committee of Abenaki women. This year, she coordinates a project on the inclusion of LGBTQI+/bi-spiritual people. Jessica is connected to the land, she goes fishing and she recently started hunting as well. She has her own garden, and in the summer of 2016, she started a traditional garden and a community garden for the students of Kiuna.</p>
